(:kind :chapter :book "Reference Manual" :chapter-number 11 :title "Chapter 11 — Hygienic macros" :source-path "git://origin/main/scheme-books/reference/11-hygienic-macros.md" :size 3571 :sha256 "d911487522b58d90" :content "---\nslug: sakura-scheme-book-reference-11\ntitle: Hygienic macros\nbook: reference\nchapter: 11\nof: 16\npart: II\napp: scheme-repl\npalette: book-standard\ncanonical: true\nowner: docs-team (Lane 6)\nphilosopher-lens: [wittgenstein-late]\nstatus: draft\nlast-reviewed: 2026-07-12\nprev: 10-a-tiny-compiler\nnext: 12-first-class-continuations\n---\n\n# Chapter 11 — Hygienic macros\n\nChapter 4 introduced macros. This chapter deepens: *why hygienic\nmacros over `defmacro`*, and *how* the pattern-based rewriter avoids\nthe classic variable-capture bugs.\n\n> **Sakura says**\n>\n> A macro reshapes code before it runs. A hygienic macro reshapes\n> code without accidentally borrowing your variables. Hygiene is why\n> `let` inside a macro doesn't clobber the caller's `let`.\n\n## The problem `defmacro` has\n\n```sakura-scheme\n; Classic defmacro pattern (NOT what we use)\n(defmacro my-swap (a b)\n  `(let ((tmp ,a))\n     (set! ,a ,b)\n     (set! ,b tmp)))\n\n; Caller writes:\n(let ((tmp 5))\n  (my-swap x tmp))   ; BUG: caller's `tmp` collides with macro's `tmp`\n```\n\nThe macro captured `tmp` unintentionally. `defmacro` doesn't know\nabout scope. The caller's `tmp` got clobbered.\n\n## Hygienic macros — pattern-based\n\n```sakura-scheme\n(define-syntax swap!\n  (syntax-rules ()\n    ((_ a b)\n     (let ((tmp a))\n       (set! a b)\n       (set! b tmp)))))\n```\n\nThe `let` here creates a *fresh* `tmp` at expansion time — the\ncompiler ensures the identifier doesn't clash with any name in the\ncaller's scope. No capture. Just works.\n\n## Syntax patterns\n\n```sakura-scheme\n(define-syntax when\n  (syntax-rules ()\n    ((_ test body ...)\n     (if test (begin body ...) '()))))\n\n(define-syntax unless\n  (syntax-rules ()\n    ((_ test body ...)\n     (if test '() (begin body ...)))))\n\n(when (positive? x)\n  (display \"yes\")\n  (newline))\n```\n\nPatterns use `...` for variadic captures. Compiler unifies the\npattern with the call and expands.\n\n## Multiple patterns\n\n```sakura-scheme\n(define-syntax my-cond\n  (syntax-rules (else)\n    ((_)          '())\n    ((_ (else e ...))  (begin e ...))\n    ((_ (test e ...) rest ...)\n     (if test (begin e ...) (my-cond rest ...)))))\n\n(my-cond\n  ((< x 0) 'negative)\n  ((= x 0) 'zero)\n  (else    'positive))\n```\n\nAlternatives in order. The compiler picks the first matching pattern.\n\n## When to reach for a macro\n\n- **Control flow that's not first-class** — `when`, `unless`, custom\n  loops, pattern matchers.\n- **Domain-specific syntax** — a mini language for animations,\n  queries, tests.\n- **Elimination of ceremony** — turning three lines into one when the\n  three lines were always the same.\n\n## When NOT to reach for a macro\n\n- When a **function** would work. Functions are easier to debug,\n  compose, and reason about.\n- When the pattern shows up twice. Twice is not a pattern. Three\n  times is.\n- When the macro would introduce silent state or non-local effects.\n\n## Sakura's use of macros\n\nHer `installFrpGrammar`, `installCardVerbs`, and similar Wave-1\nslice installers register verbs into the registry — those aren't\nmacros in the syntax-rules sense; they're runtime registrations of\nJavaScript-backed primitives. Book of Reference — engine architecture\ncovers that pattern.\n\nWhere she uses actual macros: `when`, `unless`, `my-cond`, custom\n`with-timeout`, `with-fuel` — small syntactic sugar on top of the\ncore interpreter.\n\n## Cross-links\n\n- [[book-of-reference]] ch 4 — first look at macros.\n- [[book-of-reference]] ch 12 — first-class continuations.\n- [[book-of-slat]] ch 11 — auto-assembly (macro-adjacent registry pattern).\n\n---\n\nTurn the page.\n")
